title: Add dll probe path so that the right DirectML.dll is loaded while running C# tests
body: **Description**: The C# tests dll seems to load the system DirectML.dll shipped with the OS (which is stale compared to what the latest onnxruntime DirectML EP actually needs). This is because when `dotnet.exe` is invoked, DirectML.dll is searched for in the path containing `dotnet.exe` and when it doesn't find it, it falls back to using the system dll. To solve this, add the folder containing the required DirectML.dll (which is the bin folder of the C# tests) to the dll probe path so that it is loaded by the test process ahead of the system dll.

title: Exclude a few python tests for the DML EP
body:
**Description**: 

Some Python tests need to be disabled for an ORT wheel built with DML (and not CUDA) support because they are not supported by the DML EP or they don't pass some tests. 

We keep these tests covered for cases where both the DML EP and CUDA EP are built into the wheel (to have them covered in the CI pipelines which uses the combination). The tests will pass in CI because the CUDA EP has higher precedence than the DML EP and when all nodes are assigned to CUDA, these tests run fine. 

The problem is that there in nothing in CI that tests a "pure" DML only Python wheel (a real world user would build only this) and hence we won't catch any failures. Opened a backlog task (897037) to address this.

**Motivation and Context**
Fix https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/5130

title: Adding an option for cudnn conv algorithms.
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
Adding an C API so that users can decide how to choose cudnn conv algorithms:

ORT_API_STATUS_IMPL(OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_CUDA_CONV_ALGO, _In_ OrtSessionOptions* options, int device_id, int conv_algo)

for conv_algo:
     0: expensive exhaustive benchmarking using cudnnFindConvolutionForwardAlgorithmEx
     1: lightweight heuristic based search using cudnnGetConvolutionForwardAlgorithm_v7
     2: default algorithm using CUDNN_CONVOLUTION_FWD_ALGO_IMPLICIT_PRECOMP_GEMM

**Motivation and Context**
In previous design, cuda conv always run cudnnFindConvolutionForwardAlgorithmEx to find the best suitable conv algorithm if input shape changes, which is very expensive. This change will let users decide which conv algorithm search strategy to use.

- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
Previously, if the input shapes changes, the cuda conv perf is very poor due the reason mentioned above. This change solved this problem.

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Use onecore umbrella lib in onecore builds
body:
**Description**: The windowsapp.lib umbrella was being used in non-appcontainer builds. The reasoning behind it was some bug in the onecore apiset umbrellas that exists/used to exist and caused either a BVT validation failure, or a downlevel break (I wasn't the one who authored the changes and don't know the details). This workaround used to work because the windowsapp.lib umbrella is similar to the onecore apiset umbrella (both link to apisets and expose about the same set of functions).

After the latest Windows SDK update, it seems like linking to windowsapp.lib is exposing the appcontainer implementation of the delayload wrappers, and causing delayloading to fail. I'm removing the old workaround and linking to the correct umbrella libs if the build is for onecore.

This change probably deserves a downlevel run to make sure it's working. I'm waiting on the nuget pipelines (the GPU pool takes a bit) and will take a manual look into the imported symbols as soon as possible.

title: NCHWc optimizer fixes for quantized models
body:
**Description**: This updates the NCHWc transformer to not interfere with quantized convolution models, based on observations from internal models.

**Motivation and Context**
The MaxPool transformation in the NCHWc transformer didn't check the type of the input tensor, so it incorrectly altered a quantized CNN that contained MaxPool<uint8_t>. Added checks for this and a test case.

The optimizer also has been changed to not force a reorder to NCHWc for GlobalAveragePool/GlobalMaxPool. Typically for float32 CNNs, the tensor is already in NCHWc format and the runtime should avoid going back to NCHW to do this operation. But for a quantized CNN, the float tensor usually came from a DequantizeLinear. It's cheaper to run the NCHW version of GlobalAveragePool/GlobalMaxPool instead. This saves a few % for one quantized CNN. MaxPool/AveragePool behavior is unchanged for now.

title: Add FusedMatMul contrib op
body:
**Description**: 
1. Add new contrib op FusedMatMul which is same as the TransposeMatMul Op. This is done so that the op name better reflects the op behavior. 
2. Fuse CPU kernels for MatMul, FusedMatMul and TransposeMatMul
3. Update graph optimizers to use FusedMatMul instead of TransposeMatMul.
3. Update relevant tests, test generation scripts and test data

**Motivation and Context**
- Changing the op name to better reflect it's behavior. To preserve backward compatibility had to create a new op instead of just renaming the existing op as this OP has been part of ORT releases. Going forward FusedMatMul should be used instead of TransposeMatMul.

title: Provide option to let layernorm stash mean/var as fp32 or bfloat16
body:
**Description**: provide a training option to set layernorm's stash data type as bfloat16 or fp32

**Motivation and Context**
- Previously for layernorm we always stash mean/var as fp32, but some research shows when train with bfloat16, it make sense to stash as bfloat16, since it has the same dynamic range. So provide that training option seems reasonable
